<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="174" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,152,1037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,152,179]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Discussion.</emphasis>
According to the published spider records available in the World Spider Catalog, Neotropical Tetrablemmids occurs from 
<collectingCountry box="[434,520,182,208]" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">México</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[556,627,182,208]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, mainly in soil and leaf litter of dry and humid forests, from 
<quantity metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.4" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" unit="m" value="540.0" valueMax="1000.0" valueMin="80.0">80 to 1000 m</quantity>
a.s.l (
<bibRefCitation author="World Spider Catalog" box="[241,565,218,244]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" refId="ref6080" refString="World Spider Catalog (2019) World Spider Catalog. Version 20.0. Natural History Museum of Bern, Bern. Available from: http: // wsc. nmbe. ch (accessed 11 June 2019)" type="url" year="2019">World Spider Catalog, 2019</bibRefCitation>
). However, this family seems to have low abundance in inventories of spider communities, sometimes with just one or two individuals collected, as noticed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bonaldo, A. B. &amp; Dias, S." box="[1101,1372,254,280]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" pagination="357 - 372" refId="ref4881" refString="Bonaldo, A. B. &amp; Dias, S. (2010) A structured inventory of spiders (Arachnida, Araneae) in natural and artificial forest gaps at Porto Urucu, Western Brazilian Amazonia. Acta Amazonica, 40 (2), 357 - 372. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0044 - 59672010000200014" type="journal article" year="2010">Bonaldo &amp; Días (2010)</bibRefCitation>
from Brazilian Amazon and 
<bibRefCitation author="Edwards, R. L. &amp; Edwards, A. D." box="[412,728,290,316]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" pagination="599 - 609" refId="ref4992" refString="Edwards, R. L. &amp; Edwards, A. D. (2007) Life history and ecology of the armored spider Monoblemma muchmorei (Araneae, Tetrablemmidae). Journal of Arachnology, 34, 599 - 609. https: // doi. org / 10.1636 / S 04 - 109.1" type="journal article" year="2007">Edwards &amp; Edwards (2007)</bibRefCitation>
in bamboo leaf litter from 
<collectingCountry box="[1038,1175,290,317]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
. In 
<collectingCountry box="[1219,1332,290,316]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, the only official record of a tetrablemmid was given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Shear, W. A." box="[669,814,326,352]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" pagination="1 - 46" refId="ref5790" refString="Shear, W. A. (1978) Taxonomic notes on the armored spiders of the families Tetrablemmidae and Pacullidae. American Museum Novitates, 2650, 1 - 46." type="journal article" year="1978">Shear (1978)</bibRefCitation>
who examined 
<specimenCount box="[989,1073,326,352]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" type="male">3 males</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[1126,1247,326,352]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" type="female">10 females</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shear" authorityYear="1978" class="Arachnida" family="Tetrablemmidae" genus="Monoblemma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="muchmorei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Monoblemma muchmorei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected in Villavicencio (
<collectingRegion box="[588,787,362,389]" country="Colombia" name="Meta" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Meta department</collectingRegion>
), in the confluence of the humid forests from the Eastern slopes of Cordillera Oriental mountains and the Eastern plains of the country (Villavicencio-Apure dry forests according to WWF ecoregions system). However, this species was described based on material from 
<collectingCountry box="[1278,1436,434,460]" name="Virgin Islands" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Virgin Islands</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry box="[161,210,470,496]" name="United States of America" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">U.S.</collectingCountry>
) (
<figureCitation box="[235,301,469,496]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1966,1991]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1073,1932]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,1073,1932]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Monoblemma muchmorei (AMNH) female paratype from Virgin Islands (U.S.). A. Dorsal view, B. Ventral view. Photographs courtesy of Norman Platnick and Lily Berniker (AMNH)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3248505/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,152,1037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">
In this paper, 
<specimenCount box="[353,429,506,532]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" type="male">3 male</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[484,582,506,532]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" type="female">4 female</specimenCount>
specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="García &amp; Martínez &amp; Ahumada-C, 2019" authorityName="García &amp; Martínez &amp; Ahumada-C" authorityYear="2019" box="[744,886,506,533]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetrablemmidae" genus="Caraimatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brescoviti" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[744,886,506,533]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">C. brescoviti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[894,984,506,532]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[894,984,506,532]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
were collected in the Colombian Caribbean region from localities close to Montes de María, where some fragments of dry forest (Guajira-Barranquilla xeric scrub WWF ecoregion) and some humid forests (Magdalena-Urabá moist forests WWF ecoregion) still exist (
<figureCitation box="[160,228,614,641]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1457,1482]" captionTargetBox="[353,1237,187,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[340,1247,181,1437]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Map showing the distribution of Caraimatta species and Monoblemma muchmorei in America (the detailed area shows the distribution of Caraimatta brescoviti sp. nov. in the tropical dry forest of Caribbean region of Colombia)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3248507/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,152,1037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">
Unhappily, the Tropical Dry Forest (TDF) is an endangered ecosystem in 
<collectingCountry box="[1016,1126,650,676]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Colombia</collectingCountry>
being affected by anthropic activities such as agriculture, logging and livestock (
<bibRefCitation author="Garcia, H. &amp; Corzo, G. &amp; Isaacs, P. &amp; Etter, A." box="[748,967,686,712]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" pagination="229 - 251" refId="ref5283" refString="Garcia, H., Corzo, G., Isaacs, P. &amp; Etter, A. (2014) Capitulo 8: Distribucion y estado actual de los remanentes del bioma de Bosque Seco Tropical en Colombia: insumos para su gestion. In: Pizano, C. &amp; Garcia, H. (Eds.), El Bosque Seco Tropical en Colombia. Instituto de Investigacion de Recursos Biologicos Alexander von Humboldt (IAvH). Bogota, D. C., pp. 229 - 251." type="book chapter" year="2014">
García 
<emphasis box="[833,897,686,712]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">et al.,</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). The TDF has been reduced to 3% of its original extension, only 5% of which is included in protected areas of the National System of Protected Areas (Sistema Nacional de Áreas Protegidas-SINAP). The departments in the Caribbean region, 
<collectingRegion box="[1176,1240,758,784]" country="Colombia" name="Cesar" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Cesar</collectingRegion>
(21.8%), 
<collectingRegion box="[1352,1436,758,784]" country="Colombia" name="Bolivar" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Bolívar</collectingRegion>
(18.4%), 
<collectingRegion box="[256,380,794,820]" country="Colombia" name="Magdalena" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Magdalena</collectingRegion>
(12.1%) and 
<collectingRegion box="[531,595,794,820]" country="Colombia" name="Sucre" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Sucre</collectingRegion>
(3.9%) contributes the most to the Colombian TDF coverage (
<bibRefCitation author="Garcia, H. &amp; Corzo, G. &amp; Isaacs, P. &amp; Etter, A." pageId="6" pageNumber="174" pagination="229 - 251" refId="ref5283" refString="Garcia, H., Corzo, G., Isaacs, P. &amp; Etter, A. (2014) Capitulo 8: Distribucion y estado actual de los remanentes del bioma de Bosque Seco Tropical en Colombia: insumos para su gestion. In: Pizano, C. &amp; Garcia, H. (Eds.), El Bosque Seco Tropical en Colombia. Instituto de Investigacion de Recursos Biologicos Alexander von Humboldt (IAvH). Bogota, D. C., pp. 229 - 251." type="book chapter" year="2014">
García 
<emphasis box="[1374,1436,794,820]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">et al.,</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
, table 8.3), and are potential localities of interest for the discovery of further tetrablemmids.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,152,1037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">
Finally, although there are several studies about spiders in Colombian TDF (
<bibRefCitation author="Cabra-Garcia, J. &amp; Chacon, P. &amp; Valderrama, C." box="[1057,1346,866,892]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" pagination="90 - 91" refId="ref4944" refString="Cabra-Garcia, J., Chacon, P. &amp; Valderrama, C. (2010) Riqueza y composicion de aranas en diferentes coberturas vegetales del Parque Natural Regional El Vinculo (Valle del Cauca, Colombia). Cespedesia, 32, 90 - 91." type="journal article" year="2010">
Cabra-García 
<emphasis box="[1216,1279,866,892]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">et al.,</emphasis>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Florez, E." pageId="6" pageNumber="174" pagination="37 - 57" refId="ref5173" refString="Florez, E. (1997) Estudio de la comunidad de Aranas en el bosque seco tropical de la Estacion Biologica El Vinculo. Cespedesia, 69 (22), 37 - 57." type="journal article" year="1997">Flórez, 1997</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Florez, E." box="[220,278,902,928]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" pagination="173 - 192" refId="ref5209" refString="Florez, E. (1998) Estructura de comunidades de aranas (Araneae) en el departamento del Valle, suroccidente de Colombia. Caldasia, 20 (2), 173 - 192." type="journal article" year="1998">1998</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Florez, E." box="[290,349,902,928]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" pagination="37 - 51" refId="ref5245" refString="Florez, E. (1999) Estructura y Composicion de una comunidad de Aranas de un Bosque muy seco tropical de Colombia. Boletin de Entomologia Venezolana, 14 (1), 37 - 51." type="journal article" year="1999">1999</bibRefCitation>
), very few focuse on spider inventories in TDF remnants of the Colombian Caribbean (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Escorcia, G. R. Y. &amp; Martinez, H. N. J. &amp; Silva, T. J. P." pageId="6" pageNumber="174" pagination="247 - 260" refId="ref5047" refString="Escorcia, G. R. Y., Martinez, H. N. J. &amp; Silva, T. J. P. (2012) Estudio de la diversidad de aranas de un bosque seco tropical (Bs-T) en Sabanalarga, Atlantico, Colombia. Boletin Cientifico Museo Historia Natural Universidad de Caldas, 16 (1), 247 - 260." type="journal article" year="2012">
Escorcia 
<emphasis box="[190,251,938,964]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">et al.,</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Quijano, C. L. &amp; Martinez, H. N." box="[327,621,937,964]" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" pagination="381 - 396" refId="ref5656" refString="Quijano, C. L. &amp; Martinez, H. N. (2015) Variacion temporal de la araneofauna (Arachnida: Araneae) en un fragmento de Bosque Seco Tropical (BST), en el departamento del Atlantico, Colombia. Boletin Cientifico Museo Historia Natural Universidad de Caldas, 19 (2), 381 - 396." type="journal article" year="2015">Quijano &amp; Martínez, 2015</bibRefCitation>
, both for 
<collectingRegion box="[724,963,938,965]" country="Colombia" name="Atlantico" pageId="6" pageNumber="174">Atlántico department</collectingRegion>
). Because of their similarity to other spider families (e.g. 
<taxonomicName box="[302,428,974,1001]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Oonopidae</taxonomicName>
), many tetrablemmid specimens may have gone unnoticed in biological collections, and we suspect that many new records and species remain to be discovered both in the field and in the local repositories.
</paragraph>
